<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
  waywallen-display-v1

  Wire protocol between a display client (libwaywallen_display, or any
  other conforming consumer) and the waywallen daemon. Spoken over
  SOCK_STREAM Unix Domain Socket at $XDG_RUNTIME_DIR/waywallen/display.sock.

  Role model:
    client  = display (passive output device; advertises size/name, does
              not choose content)
    server  = manager (waywallen daemon; decides which renderer feeds
              which display, with what source_rect/dest_rect/transform)

  Wire format (Wayland-inspired positional binary):

    header: 4 bytes
      u16 opcode
      u16 total_length_in_bytes  (including the 4-byte header)

    body: positional args, 4-byte aligned

      u32/i32/f32 = 4 bytes LE
      u64/i64/f64 = 8 bytes LE
      string      = [u32 len_including_NUL] [utf8...] [NUL] [pad to 4]
      array<T>    = [u32 count] [count * sizeof(T)] [pad to 4]
      rect        = 4 * f32 = 16 bytes  (x, y, w, h)
      kv_list     = [u32 count] [count * (string key, string value)]

    fds: passed out-of-band via SCM_RIGHTS ancillary data. Order defined
         per-message. The inline body never contains an fd word.

  Invariants:

    - The first Request on a new connection MUST be `hello`.
    - The first Event in reply MUST be `welcome`.
    - `register_display` MUST be sent exactly once per connection, after
      the hello/welcome exchange.
    - `buffer_generation` is monotonically increasing.
    - `config_generation` is monotonically increasing and independent of
      buffer_generation.
    - `seq` is globally monotonic per stream, not reset across rebinds.
    - A new `bind_buffers` implicitly retires all prior generations. The
      display MUST NOT send `buffer_release` for any retired generation.
    - Between receipt of `bind_buffers` and the corresponding
      `set_config`, the display is in PENDING_CONFIG and MUST NOT accept
      any `frame_ready`.
    - Every `frame_ready` carries exactly TWO fds (in order):
        1. acquire sync_fd     — dma_fence sync_file the display MUST
           wait on before sampling.
        2. release_syncobj fd  — daemon-allocated drm_syncobj (binary).
           The display signals it (via SYNC_FILE → IMPORT_SYNC_FILE, or
           by signaling the imported Vulkan binary semaphore from its
           own GPU work) once it has finished sampling. The signal IS
           the release — there is no separate `buffer_release` request
           in v1.
        The display owns both fds and MUST close them after import.
    - Display never panics/aborts; any wire or protocol error results
      in on_disconnected and cleanup. Server is free to crash.

  Version: 3

  Versioning policy (daemon-authoritative):
    - `hello.client_protocol_version` is a single u32 declared by the
      client. The daemon owns the supported range [MIN..=MAX]; any
      client version outside that range is rejected with
      `error{code = WW_ERR_VERSION_UNSUPPORTED, message = ...}` and the
      connection is closed. The client does NOT verify daemon version;
      `welcome.server_version` is informational/diagnostic only.
    - The version number is independent of the lib's API/ABI version
      (libwaywallen_display SO version) — it tracks ONLY this XML's
      `<protocol version="...">` attribute.

  Error codes (carried in `error.code`):
    1 — WW_ERR_PROTO_NAME_MISMATCH    (hello.protocol string mismatch)
    2 — WW_ERR_VERSION_UNSUPPORTED    (hello.client_protocol_version
                                       outside daemon's supported range)

  v2 (modifier negotiation):
    - Consumer ships `consumer_caps` request immediately after
      `register_display`. Carries fourcc/modifier/plane_count
      grids plus device_uuid + sync_caps + color_caps + mem_hints
      mirroring the producer-side `format_caps` event in ipc_v2.
    - Daemon pairs the consumer's caps with the bound renderer's caps,
      picks an intersection (LINEAR cross-vendor / non-LINEAR same-GPU)
      and only THEN dispatches `bind_buffers` for this consumer.
    - Consumer sends `bind_failed` request on import failure; daemon
      blacklists that (fourcc, modifier) pair on this consumer and
      retries the picker. Non-terminal — only `error` is terminal.

  v3 (explicit version negotiation):
    - `hello` carries `client_protocol_version: u32` so the daemon can
      reject too-old / too-new clients deterministically instead of
      relying on the protocol-name string suffix.
    - `welcome.features` is now informational. The daemon guarantees
      the feature set implied by the negotiated version; clients MUST
      NOT gate on features field contents.

  v5 (features-first modifier filter):
    - `consumer_caps` drops the `usages` per-modifier u32 array. The
      daemon's picker never consumed it; both peers now filter
      modifiers locally by `VkFormatFeatureFlags` and only the
      surviving (fourcc, modifier, plane_count) tuples hit the wire.
    - Wire-incompatible with v4. v4 clients send an extra `usages[]`
      array that decode now fails on; daemon rejects them via
      hello.client_protocol_version range check.

  v6 (unbind ack):
    - New request `unbind_done` (opcode 11): display→daemon ack that
      an `unbind` event was received and host-side teardown has been
      initiated. The daemon waits for this (with a short timeout)
      before issuing `Shutdown` to the producer that owned the
      unbound pool, so the producer's exported acquire dma_fence
      doesn't get force-cancelled mid-blit by the consumer.
    - Wire-compatible with v5 except for the new request — v5 clients
      that never send `unbind_done` still work (daemon falls back to
      the timeout). v6 clients on a v5 daemon would just have their
      `unbind_done` silently ignored as an unknown opcode if the
      daemon's range allowed v6 (it won't — daemon only accepts ≥6
      once it advertises v6).

  v7 (window-state reporting for daemon-side autopause):
    - New request `window_state` (opcode 12): consumer→daemon advisory
      bitmask describing which kinds of windows currently cover this
      display. Fire-and-forget; consumers that have no window-state
      source (GNOME extension before window-management support,
      headless tests, anything non-KDE) simply never send it — the
      daemon defaults the display to "no covering windows".
    - Daemon owns the per-display autopause Mode / ResumeMs settings
      and is the only side that decides Pause/Play. Consumers MUST
      NOT debounce or filter; just emit on every observed change.
    - Wire-compatible with v6 except for the new opcode. v6 clients
      that never send `window_state` keep working (daemon defaults
      that display to "no autopause condition met").

  Informational features (welcome.features, advisory only in v3+):
    "explicit_sync_fd"           — acquire fence as dma_fence sync_file.
    "drm_syncobj_release"        — release fence as drm_syncobj fd.
    "modifier_negotiation_v1"    — consumer_caps + bind_failed plumbing.
  Optional features (reserved): "color_management", "hdr"
-->
<protocol name="waywallen_display" version="7">

  <!-- ==================================================================
       REQUESTS  (display -> manager)
       ================================================================== -->

  <!--
    Opening handshake. Must be the first message on a new connection.
    Server verifies:
      1. `protocol == PROTOCOL_NAME` (e.g. "waywallen-display-v3"); on
         mismatch replies with `error{code=1}` and closes.
      2. `client_protocol_version` is within the daemon's supported
         [MIN..=MAX] range; on miss replies with `error{code=2}` and
         closes.
    On success the server replies with `welcome`.

    `client_version` is a free-form human-readable string (e.g. lib
    SemVer) used purely for logs/diagnostics. The version gate is
    `client_protocol_version`.
  -->
  <request name="hello" opcode="1">
    <arg name="protocol" type="string"/>
    <arg name="client_name" type="string"/>
    <arg name="client_version" type="string"/>
    <arg name="client_protocol_version" type="u32"/>
  </request>

  <!--
    Advertise this display as an output device. The manager uses the
    advertised dimensions (+ any properties) to pick content and compute
    source_rect / dest_rect. Sent once per connection, after welcome.

    `refresh_mhz` is millihertz (e.g. 60000 = 60.000 Hz). Zero means
    unknown; manager may pick a conservative frame budget.

    `drm_render_major` / `drm_render_minor` identify the DRM render
    node of the GPU this display will sample dmabufs on (i.e. the GPU
    backing the EGL/Vulkan context the consumer uses to import frames).
    The manager compares this against each renderer's GPU id to decide
    whether dmabuf placement must be promoted to HOST_VISIBLE/GTT for
    cross-GPU PRIME import.

    A client that cannot resolve its render node (driver lacks
    `EGL_EXT_device_query` / `VK_EXT_physical_device_drm`) MUST send
    `(0, 0)`; the manager then conservatively assumes a cross-GPU path
    and asks the renderer for host-visible buffers.

    `properties` is an open-ended kv list for forward compat. v1 defines
    no keys — any unknown key is silently ignored by the server.

    `instance_id` (added in v4) is a stable identifier persisted by the
    consumer (e.g. UUID4 stored in KDE/GNOME extension config) that
    survives reconnects and DE restarts. It is used by the manager as
    the key into its per-display settings store; the empty string
    means the consumer has no stable id, in which case the manager
    falls back to indexing settings by `name` (legacy v3 behavior).
    The manager treats the value as opaque — it is not parsed.
  -->
  <request name="register_display" opcode="2">
    <arg name="name" type="string"/>
    <arg name="instance_id" type="string"/>
    <arg name="width" type="u32"/>
    <arg name="height" type="u32"/>
    <arg name="refresh_mhz" type="u32"/>
    <arg name="drm_render_major" type="u32"/>
    <arg name="drm_render_minor" type="u32"/>
    <arg name="properties" type="kv_list"/>
  </request>

  <!--
    Display size/properties changed (window resize, monitor mode switch).
    Fire-and-forget: display does not wait for an ack and keeps
    rendering with its current SetConfig. Manager may respond with a
    new `set_config` to adapt `dest_rect`, or may ignore.
  -->
  <request name="update_display" opcode="3">
    <arg name="width" type="u32"/>
    <arg name="height" type="u32"/>
    <arg name="properties" type="kv_list"/>
  </request>

  <!--
    NOTE: opcode 4 is intentionally unused. v1's `buffer_release`
    request was removed; release is now signaled by the display
    flipping the `release_syncobj` fd that arrived alongside the
    matching `frame_ready` (see opcode 5). Releasing a slot is
    fire-and-forget on the GPU side: the daemon polls the syncobj
    and only then merges the fence into the producer's release
    timeline.
  -->

  <!--
    Clean shutdown marker from the display side. After sending `bye`
    the display closes its write half; it may still drain pending
    events until the server closes the socket.
  -->
  <request name="bye" opcode="5">
  </request>

  <!--
    Consumer capability declaration — sent immediately after
    `register_display`. Mirrors `format_caps` in waywallen-ipc-v2;
    same parallel-array layout, same bit definitions for sync_caps /
    color_caps / mem_hints. The daemon stores it alongside the
    renderer's caps and gates `bind_buffers` dispatch on a successful
    `negotiate::pick(producer, consumer)`.

    Encoding: see waywallen-ipc-v2 `format_caps` doc. Validation:
    modifiers.len == plane_counts.len == sum(mod_counts).
  -->
  <request name="consumer_caps" opcode="6">
    <arg name="fourccs" type="array" element="u32"/>
    <arg name="mod_counts" type="array" element="u32"/>
    <arg name="modifiers" type="array" element="u64"/>
    <arg name="plane_counts" type="array" element="u32"/>
    <arg name="device_uuid" type="array" element="u32"/>
    <arg name="driver_uuid" type="array" element="u32"/>
    <arg name="drm_render_major" type="u32"/>
    <arg name="drm_render_minor" type="u32"/>
    <arg name="mem_hints" type="u32"/>
    <arg name="sync_caps" type="u32"/>
    <arg name="color_caps" type="u32"/>
    <arg name="extent_max_w" type="u32"/>
    <arg name="extent_max_h" type="u32"/>
  </request>

  <!--
    Consumer report that a daemon-issued `bind_buffers` could not be
    imported on this device (e.g. `eglCreateImageKHR` returned
    EGL_NO_IMAGE_KHR for the (fourcc, modifier) pair the daemon picked).
    Non-terminal: the daemon adds (fourcc, modifier) to this consumer's
    per-peer blacklist and re-runs `negotiate::pick`. If the picker
    has nothing left it falls back to a terminal `error` event.
    `reason` codes mirror ipc-v2 bind_failed.
  -->
  <request name="bind_failed" opcode="7">
    <arg name="fourcc" type="u32"/>
    <arg name="modifier" type="u64"/>
    <arg name="reason" type="u32"/>
    <arg name="message" type="string"/>
  </request>

  <!--
    Pointer events forwarded from the consumer (display) to the manager.
    **Reserved**: the manager currently logs at debug and drops. Future
    work will route these to interactive renderers (parallax,
    click-through, in-wallpaper widgets).

    Coordinate space (all three messages):
      `x` / `y` are surface-local pixel coordinates with origin at the
      top-left of the consumer's advertised display extent (the same
      space `register_display.width`/`height` are measured in).
      Sub-pixel precision allowed for HiDPI compositors.

    Common fields:
      `timestamp_us` — monotonic, microseconds. 0 means "not provided"
                       (the manager will stamp on receipt).
      `modifiers`    — Linux KEY_* modifier bitmask (Ctrl=4, Alt=8, …).
                       0 if unknown.

    Modeled after `wl_pointer.{motion,button,axis}` to match renderer
    authors' mental model.
  -->
  <request name="pointer_motion" opcode="8">
    <arg name="x" type="f32"/>
    <arg name="y" type="f32"/>
    <arg name="timestamp_us" type="u64"/>
    <arg name="modifiers" type="u32"/>
  </request>

  <!--
    `button` is a Linux input event code (BTN_LEFT=0x110, BTN_RIGHT=0x111,
    BTN_MIDDLE=0x112, BTN_SIDE=0x113, BTN_EXTRA=0x114).
    `state` is 0 (release) or 1 (press).
  -->
  <request name="pointer_button" opcode="9">
    <arg name="x" type="f32"/>
    <arg name="y" type="f32"/>
    <arg name="button" type="u32"/>
    <arg name="state" type="u32"/>
    <arg name="timestamp_us" type="u64"/>
    <arg name="modifiers" type="u32"/>
  </request>

  <!--
    `delta_x` / `delta_y` are scroll deltas in "logical notches"
    (Qt's 120-per-notch convention divided by 120; Wayland's
    wl_pointer.axis units divided by 10 for wheel sources). Diagonal
    scroll fits in a single message.

    `source` discriminates the input device:
      0 — wheel       (discrete clicks, e.g. mouse wheel)
      1 — finger      (touchpad two-finger scroll)
      2 — continuous  (smooth scrollers, hi-res wheels)
  -->
  <request name="pointer_axis" opcode="10">
    <arg name="x" type="f32"/>
    <arg name="y" type="f32"/>
    <arg name="delta_x" type="f32"/>
    <arg name="delta_y" type="f32"/>
    <arg name="source" type="u32"/>
    <arg name="timestamp_us" type="u64"/>
    <arg name="modifiers" type="u32"/>
  </request>

  <!--
    Acknowledge that an `unbind` event with `buffer_generation` was
    received and host-side teardown has been initiated (the on_textures
    _releasing callback fired and the consumer's pending-pool list
    captured the released imports). The acknowledgement does NOT
    promise that the consumer's GPU has actually finished sampling —
    that's a separate guarantee provided by the kernel/driver once the
    producer's acquire dma_fence signals.

    The manager waits for this ack with a short timeout before issuing
    `Shutdown` to the producer that owned the pool, so the producer's
    in-flight GPU work isn't force-cancelled while the consumer is
    still blitting from it.

    Fire-and-forget on the display side: send and move on. If the
    socket dies before this is sent, the daemon's connection-close
    handler treats EOF as an implicit ack for any pending unbinds.
  -->
  <request name="unbind_done" opcode="11">
    <arg name="buffer_generation" type="u64"/>
  </request>

  <!--
    Periodic / on-change window-state report from the consumer side.
    Used by the daemon's per-display autopause feature: each consumer
    (e.g. the KDE wallpaper plasmoid) computes a small bitmask
    describing windows that currently cover its display and emits a
    new `window_state` whenever it changes. The daemon translates the
    bitmask + per-display autopause Mode setting into renderer
    Pause/Play.

    Fire-and-forget. Consumers MUST NOT debounce, time-filter, or
    otherwise interpret the bits — the daemon owns all policy. Bit
    positions:

      bit 0  WW_WIN_HAS_NON_MINIMIZED  some mapped (non-minimized)
                                       window covers this display.
      bit 1  WW_WIN_HAS_ACTIVE         some window on this display
                                       has keyboard focus.
      bit 2  WW_WIN_HAS_MAXIMIZED      some window is H+V maximized
                                       (NOT counting fullscreen).
      bit 3  WW_WIN_HAS_FULLSCREEN     some window is fullscreen.
      bits 4..31  reserved, MUST be 0 on send, MUST be ignored on
                  receive.

    The implicit default for any display that never sends this
    request is `flags = 0` (no autopause trigger).
  -->
  <request name="window_state" opcode="12">
    <arg name="flags" type="u32"/>
  </request>


  <!-- ==================================================================
       EVENTS  (manager -> display)
       ================================================================== -->

  <!--
    Reply to `hello`. Both fields are advisory in v3+:
      - `server_version` is a free-form human-readable string for logs.
      - `features` lists the daemon-guaranteed feature set implied by
        the negotiated protocol version. Clients MUST NOT gate on the
        contents — version negotiation has already happened by the
        time `welcome` is sent, and the daemon is authoritative.
  -->
  <event name="welcome" opcode="1">
    <arg name="server_version" type="string"/>
    <arg name="features" type="array" element="string"/>
  </event>

  <!--
    Ack of `register_display`. `display_id` is an opaque u64 assigned
    by the manager, intended for logs and debugging only.
  -->
  <event name="display_accepted" opcode="2">
    <arg name="display_id" type="u64"/>
  </event>

  <!--
    A new set of DMA-BUF backing buffers is being bound to this
    display. All previously-bound buffers (if any) are implicitly
    retired; the display MUST stop using any textures derived from
    the prior generation and MUST NOT send buffer_release messages
    for retired frames.

    `count` is the number of buffers in the pool. `planes_per_buffer`
    is 1 for single-plane formats (most DRM_FORMAT_* cases) and >1
    for multi-plane (e.g. YUV). The attached fds are ordered
    buffer-major, plane-minor:

      [ b0p0, b0p1, ..., b0p(P-1),
        b1p0, b1p1, ..., b1p(P-1),
        ...
        b(N-1)p0, ..., b(N-1)p(P-1) ]

    Total fds = count * planes_per_buffer.

    `stride`, `plane_offset`, and `size` arrays follow the same
    buffer-major, plane-minor ordering and have the same length as
    the fd array.

    After `bind_buffers` the display is in PENDING_CONFIG and MUST
    wait for a matching `set_config` before accepting `frame_ready`.
  -->
  <event name="bind_buffers" opcode="3">
    <arg name="buffer_generation" type="u64"/>
    <arg name="count" type="u32"/>
    <arg name="width" type="u32"/>
    <arg name="height" type="u32"/>
    <arg name="fourcc" type="u32"/>
    <arg name="modifier" type="u64"/>
    <arg name="planes_per_buffer" type="u32"/>
    <arg name="stride" type="array" element="u32"/>
    <arg name="plane_offset" type="array" element="u32"/>
    <arg name="size" type="array" element="u64"/>
    <fds count_expr="count * planes_per_buffer"/>
  </event>

  <!--
    Tell the display how to compose its output. `source_rect` is in
    texture-pixel coordinates (the buffer_generation's width/height
    space). `dest_rect` is in display-pixel coordinates (the last
    advertised register/update_display width/height).

    `transform` follows the Wayland wl_output.transform enum for
    the low two bits:
       0 = identity (0°)
       1 = rotated 90° CCW
       2 = rotated 180°
       3 = rotated 270° CCW
    Bit 7 (0x80) = horizontal flip applied before rotation.
    All other bits are reserved and MUST be zero in v1.

    `clear_color` is used to fill display pixels outside `dest_rect`
    (letterbox bars in keep-aspect fit). RGBA, non-premultiplied,
    straight alpha, sRGB.

    `config_generation` is monotonic and independent of
    buffer_generation. Manager guarantees that before sending any
    `frame_ready` with a new buffer_generation it has already sent
    at least one `set_config` for that buffer_generation.
  -->
  <event name="set_config" opcode="4">
    <arg name="config_generation" type="u64"/>
    <arg name="source_rect" type="rect"/>
    <arg name="dest_rect" type="rect"/>
    <arg name="transform" type="u32"/>
    <arg name="clear_r" type="f32"/>
    <arg name="clear_g" type="f32"/>
    <arg name="clear_b" type="f32"/>
    <arg name="clear_a" type="f32"/>
  </event>

  <!--
    Producer has a new frame available in `buffer_index` of the
    current buffer_generation. The display MUST wait on the attached
    `acquire sync_fd` before sampling the texture, and signal the
    attached `release_syncobj` fd from its release GPU work — the
    signal is the release; v1 has no `buffer_release` request.

    Two fds are attached, in order:

      [0] acquire sync_fd  — dma_fence sync_file (as produced by
          `vkGetSemaphoreFdKHR(SYNC_FD)` or `eglDupNativeFenceFDANDROID`).
          Single-use; the display imports it (TEMPORARY) and closes
          the fd.

      [1] release_syncobj fd  — daemon-allocated drm_syncobj (binary,
          unsignaled). Import via `vkImportSemaphoreFdKHR(OPAQUE_FD)`
          and signal it from the GPU submit that consumes the buffer,
          OR signal directly via `DRM_IOCTL_SYNCOBJ_IMPORT_SYNC_FILE`
          using the sync_file produced by your release work.

    `seq` is globally monotonic per connection; it does not reset
    across `bind_buffers` rebinds.
  -->
  <event name="frame_ready" opcode="5">
    <arg name="buffer_generation" type="u64"/>
    <arg name="buffer_index" type="u32"/>
    <arg name="seq" type="u64"/>
    <fds count="2"/>
  </event>

  <!--
    Retire the current buffer_generation without binding a new one.
    Manager sends this when it wants the display to stop rendering
    (for example: the renderer was stopped, or the scheduler
    reassigned the display). The display transitions back to IDLE.

    After `unbind` the display MUST NOT send any `buffer_release`
    for the retired generation.
  -->
  <event name="unbind" opcode="6">
    <arg name="buffer_generation" type="u64"/>
  </event>

  <!--
    Protocol or server-side error. Manager MAY close the connection
    immediately after sending. From the display's point of view this
    is semantically identical to EOF + a descriptive message; the
    display handles it the same as any other disconnect.
  -->
  <event name="error" opcode="7">
    <arg name="code" type="u32"/>
    <arg name="message" type="string"/>
  </event>

</protocol>
